Introduction

Children oftentimes grow up hearing from adults how they should invest their money to start saving for their retirement as soon as they can. However, not everyone acts on this advice as they get older and start their careers. Financial institutions offer investment plans like PEPs, or personal equity plans, to their customers, but many still do not have these types of accounts. This may be because people do not know how to invest their money or that theyre worried they will just lose their money. Also, in the current economic climate, there are many people who are unable to invest even if they wanted to, because they are living paycheck to paycheck.

In recent years, there has been massive growth in the popularity of targeted advertising. One can hardly visit a website without seeing an ad related to something they purchased on Amazon or for a clothing brand from a website they recently browsed through. Targeted advertising saves companies money because they are only buying enough advertising space to ensure their intended audience sees it. This type of strategic advertising reduces marketing expenditures while attempting to maximize the return on investment from those advertisements.

The key to promoting personal equity plans using targeted advertising is understanding what type of customer will be interested in making that investment. If a financial institution is able to uncover the characteristics of the different types of people who currently have PEPs within their existing customer base, they will then be able to predict who is most likely to want to become a new customer and have a PEP. Data scientists have been able to quantify the relationship between a customers characteristics and a desired outcome through a data mining method known as association rule mining. This advancement in the world of analytics puts companies in a very advantageous position, where they are able to leverage the data they have been keeping for years in new and exciting ways.

The variables which previously contained character strings are now nominal factor variables. Next, the variables that are currently of the integer type: age, income, and children need to be discretized. This is the process of turning continuous data into discrete data by grouping the values into ranges called bins. The bins can then be treated as factors. For example, if all customers aged 20-29 are placed into a bin then they are treated as all having the same age characteristic of being in their twenties.

The five number summary for the age variable provides information on how to create the bins for the descretization.

#Take a look at the 5 number summary to decide on bins for the descretization
summary(bankdf$age)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   18.00   30.00   42.00   42.40   55.25   67.00

Since the minimum age is 18 and the maximum age is 67, the age data can be binned by decades. The first bin will be for teenagers, the second for customers in their twenties, the third for customers in their thirties, and so on. The final bin will be for customers in their sixties, since there is no data that extends beyond that bin. Note that the lower bound for the first bin is 0 and the upper bound for the final bin is 120. This way if additional data is added to the data set, it will automatically be placed in the appropriate bin without having to rewrite the code. To reflect this, the final bin is labeled as being for customers who are sixty or older. In the code, the parameter right is set equal to false so that the right bound is included in the next bin. This means that someone who is exactly age 20 will be included in the Twenties bin and not the Teenagers bin.

#Discretize the age variable. Set right = FALSE so that the right bound is included in the next bin instead of the previous.
bankdf$age <- cut(bankdf$age, breaks = c(0, 20, 30, 40, 50, 60, 120),
                  labels = c("Teenagers", "Twenties", "Thirties", "Forties",
                             "Fifties", "Sixty or Older"), right = FALSE)

Next is the income variable. The five number summary is again provided for the purpose of deciding on bins.

#Take a look at the 5 number summary to decide on bins for the descretization
summary(bankdf$income)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    5014   17264   24925   27524   36173   63130

The income data will be broken up into bins spanning intervals of $10,000. The first and last bins will not have a width of 10,000 to again accommodate any new data that is added. Since the minimum income is $5000, the first bin is set to span 0 to 15,000 while still having an effective width of 10,000 for the current data.

#Descretize the income variable by binning the different income values.
bankdf$income <- cut(bankdf$income, breaks = c(0, 15000, 25000, 35000, 45000, 
                                               55000, Inf), 
                     labels = c("0-14999", "15000-24999", "25000-34999", 
                                "35000-44999", 
                                "45000-54999", "55000+"), right = FALSE)

The last variable that must have its data type converted is children. This variable requires a different approach since it is already discrete data with values that have a natural ordering. Children is therefore converted to an ordered factor variable, meaning that having 1 child is regarded as having more than 0 children, but less than 2 children.

#Convert children to an ordered factor.
bankdf$children <- ordered(bankdf$children)

Analysis and Models

The goal of the analysis is to use association rule mining to build profiles of customers who would be interested in obtaining the new personal equity plan. The customer profiles will inform the marketing department about who to target and with what form of advertisement.

Association rule mining takes an algorithmic approach to frequent pattern analysis. It will find rules in a set of transactions that predict the occurrence of an attribute. In this case, the characteristics of a customers profile will be linked to other attributes those customers are likely to have.

Association rules are described in terms of itemsets. Each itemset is a collection of one or more items from the transaction data. In this case, each of the items is a customer attribute. Rules are primarily rated on three metrics: support, confidence, and lift.

Support describes the frequency of the itemset in the data. A support of 0.10 means that the items occur in 10% of all the itemsets. Confidence describes how often items appear together. A confidence of 0.90 means that theres a 90% probability that items appear together given that one of the items appears. Lift describes how interesting the generated association rule is. Rules with a lift value of 1 describe itemsets where the appearance of one item does not affect the appearance of another item. Rules with a lift value greater than 1 describe itemsets where the appearance of one item increases the odds of the appearance of another item, but these pairs may not occur very often. Rules with a lift value less than 1 describe itemsets where each of the items occur very often, but almost never occur together.

Figure 12 displays the 20 most frequent items in the bank data. The first column, current_act=YES, reveals that this characteristic occurs in well more than 400 of the customer profiles.

#Take a look at the frequencies of the top 20 most frequent items to see which items are most likely to appear in mined association rules.
itemFrequencyPlot(bankTransaction, topN=20, type="absolute")
title("Fig.12 Most Frequent Items in the Bank Data")

The most frequently occurring items in the bank data would be the most likely to occur frequently in any mined association rules. These rules involving these most frequent items will likely reveal patterns in the data, however it may also be useful to look at rules involving items that do not occur frequently if they have strong confidence and lift. These rules may generate the most interesting results.

The first steps of the analysis will focus on generating interesting rules to better understand the customer data. The goal is to generate between 20 and 30 strong rules that feature high lift and confidence while still featuring good support. In general circumstances, a support value of 0.3 is considered to be quite strong. The first mining starts at that level without yet setting a level of confidence just to see if any rules are generated.

#Generate rule set using the apriori algorithm
bankRules <- apriori(bankTransaction, parameter = list(supp = 0.30))

Since a support level of 0.15 generated some rules, lowering it to 0.12 is guaranteed to find more. This means the desired threshold of 20 rules would be passed without any confidence parameter being set. So, at this point, the confidence parameter was also added to make sure that the rules that are being found have high confidence. Setting the confidence level to 0.9 means that any rules generated contain itemsets that are found together at least 90% of the time they are found at all.

bankRules <- apriori(bankTransaction, parameter = list(supp = 0.12, conf = 0.9))

After increasing the confidence by 0.01, a set of 26 rules was generated. Looking at the summary of quality measures provides some initial information about the rules. The median support is approximately 0.08 which means half of the itemsets the rules were created from occur in the overall data more than 8% of the time. Since there are 600 records in the bank data, even at 8%, these items are still occurring a fair number of times. Since the confidence level was set to 0.91, it is already known that all of the rules generated have strong confidence. The levels of lift are all in the range of what is usually considered strong, with at least one rule even exceeding a lift of 2.0. This means that the rules that have been generated do feature a positive correlation between their itemsets and some level of novelty.

Since all of the rules in this set have very high confidence, this rule set will be featured in the results section as a representative set of interesting rules regarding the customer profiles.

The second goal of the analysis is to uncover strong rules that imply that a certain customer profile will want to obtain a new personal equity plan based on the behavior of existing customers. When generating association rules, the right hand side of the rule can be set. In this case, it will be set to pep=YES, meaning that the customer has a personal equity plan. To start, the support and confidence levels will be kept the same compared to the previous association rule mining.

Results

The general bank rules that were generated by the association rule mining algorithm with a minimum support level of 0.07 and minimum confidence level of 0.91 can be reordered to prioritize lift. The rules with the highest lifts will be those that are the most highly correlated among the set that has already met the requirements of being frequent and consistent.

#The rules are sorted in decreasing order by lift so the highest lift rules of the set of high confidence rules will be displayed first.
bankRules <- sort(bankRules, decreasing = TRUE, by = "lift")
#The inspect function displays the first 5 rules in the newly ordered rule set.

Interestingly, even without specifically asking for rules that will lead to a conclusion about PEP, those have been generated here. The metrics of support, confidence, and lift will be interpreted using the first rule as an example.

  • A support of approximately 0.077 means that about 7.7% of all of the transactions feature itemsets that contain the items {income=15000-24999, children=1, pep=YES}.
  • A confidence of approximately 0.94 means that about 94% of the time when {income=15000-24999, children=1} appears that {pep=YES} also appears.
  • A lift of approximately 2.06 means that this particular itemset does not appear very often (as shown by having a support of 7.7%), but when the left hand side items do appear, they very frequently are seen together with the right hand side item (as shown by having a confidence of 0.94).

To summarize these facts: almost 94% of customers with an income between $15,000 and $24,999 who have one child have a personal equity plan.

plot(bankRulesPEP)

This plot provides a nice visualization of all the customer characteristics that are involved in the set of rules targeting having a personal equity plan.

When determining which five rules to highlight as the most interesting, the main focus was selecting rules that described unique customer profiles where one or more of the left hand side items were unique to only one rule out of the five. This will create a wide variety of profiles so multiple demographics can be targeted with advertisements.

The five most interesting rules are as follows:

  1. {age=Forties, children=1, save_act=YES, current_act=YES} -> {pep=YES}

This rule has a support of 0.04, a confidence of 1, and a lift of 2.19. This rule describes a customer who is middle aged and has one child. They may or may not be married, but they have a history of activity with the bank as well as financial knowledge and responsibility. They may also be a small business owner since they have a current account. Based on their having a savings account, they may be doing well enough that they have extra money availble to invest in a PEP. The confidence value of 1 actually means that all existing customers with this profile have a PEP so potential new customers who share these characteristics would be excellent targets for the advertisements. This type of customer may be best targeted with a mailing/email advertisement as they are likely doing business with these methods of communication and will see the advertisement.

  1. {married=NO, children=0, save_act=YES, mortage=NO} -> {pep=YES}

This rule has a support of 0.05, a confidence of 0.97, and a lift of 2.1. This rule describes a customer who is single and without many financial responsibilities. They do not have children to pay for and may be renting since they do not have a mortgage. Since they have a savings account it can be inferred that they have extra money and are very likely open to investing some of that extra money in a PEP. This type of customer may be most easily targeted with TV advertisements since they would not be spending their free time with a spouse or taking care of children.

  1. {region=TOWN, married=YES, children=1} -> {pep=YES}

This rule has a support of 0.04, a confidence of 0.93, and a lift of 2.03. This rule describes a customer who has a small immediate family and has enough money to be living outside of the city in the town region. Even though it is not mentioned in the rule, there is reason to believe they may own their own home and commute to work. They seem to be fairly well off and likely have money available for investments. Since it is so common for families living in a town region to commute into the city for work, this type of customer could be targeted by billboard advertisements.

  1. {sex=MALE, married=NO, children=0, mortgage=NO} -> {pep=YES}

This rule has a support of 0.04, a confidence of 0.93, and a lift of 2.03. This rule describes an unmarried man without family responsibilities. They may be focused on their careers and making money. Since an investment is an opportunity to make more money, they are likely interested in turning their extra funds into additional profits. They do not currently have other financial responsibilities holding them back from making investments. This type of customer is likely to be reached through email or TV advertisements. Many unmarried men are at least somewhat plugged in spending time on the TV or computer.

  1. {married=YES, children=1, car=NO, save_act=YES} -> {pep=YES}

This rule has a support of 0.04, a confidence of 0.92, and a lift of 2.02. This rule describes someone who has a small immediate family and does not need a car to commute to work or run errands. Even though this is not in the rule, a likely conclusion is that this type of person lives close enough to a city that public transportation is prevalent enough to eliminate the need for a car. They may also be within walking distance of necessities like those found at a grocery store. They also have enough money to have a savings account so they are likely open to using their excess money to open a personal equity plan. This type of customer could be reached though advertisements on public transportation like on those on the insides of buses or trains, or in railway stations.

Conclusions

When advertising a product it is very important that the advertisement reaches the appropriate audience. If an advertising campaign is only seen by people who are uninterested or if it is administered in too broad of a scope, the money spent on marketing costs will likely not be recuperated from the products sales. However, if it is possible to ensure that the advertisement will be seen mostly by individuals who would be interested in the product, then potential profits can be maximized while minimizing marketing costs.

Personal equity plans are not for everyone. They require a person to have additional income that extends past their bills and require a willingness to take on the risk of making an investment. The main customer profiles that will be interested in personal equity plans are those with small immediate families who have some history of having multiple accounts with the bank, and unmarried customers, especially men, who do not have children or many financial responsibilities. Overall, the best form of advertisements, given this combination of profiles, would be TV advertisements, email campaigns, and roadside billboards. All of the customer profiles have reasons to see TV ads, whether it is because they themselves are watching TV or because they are spending time with their child while they are watching. They would see email advertisements because they are already to receiving financial information that way or because they are using email regularly to facilitate their personal business dealings. Also, many would see billboard advertisements as they commute to work, bring their child to school, or go out to meet people, as would be the case for those who are unmarried.

The process outlined in this report does not have to be a one time investigation. As targeted advertisements bring in more customers, those customers and all of their demographic and account information will be added to the customer database. As the number of samples of different customer profiles increases, new rules may be uncovered and existing rules may be strengthened or weakened. By regularly performing the association rule mining algorithms on continually expanding data sets, the targeted advertisements do not have to follow stagnant recommendations. One year the best form of advertisement may be through email campaigns, and the next year TV ads might work best. The true advantage of using data mining techniques, such as association rule mining, is the ability it gives a company to be flexible, making informed changes to their processes while allocating resources as efficiently as possible.
